					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1735419&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227422" alt="Lt Flops" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1735419)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;" >Lt Flops</a></span> <span class="odate time_1588403446 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 May 2020 07:10</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4625322">
									

<p>I will say that I felt the grossness get to me at one point, but once you power past the squick and focus on the descriptions, this Tale has <em>strong writing</em>, full-stop. The use and combination of concepts oozes (no pun intended) with the canon's ethos. As far as I'm concerned, though, if you want hardened science fiction on the Wiki, this is the place to get it. You're at the top of your game when it comes to this, Nat, and you continue to show it again and again.</p>
<p>As a brief aside though, the body horror is really not that bad if you consider the implications of SCP-3484. If I'm interpreting this and 3484 correctly, it's like this: The book details a means of separating and reconnecting the parts of the body without the baggage of sensory neurons holding you back &#8212; no sensation, no pain. To rearrange a body using this method, with the right state of mind, means ultimately achieving all sorts of things the average human could never come close to. I found it much easier to digest the descriptions with that in mind (though I would like to suggest a body horror content warning for the unsuspecting reader?). There's a lot going on here and it's all wildly creative, and frankly, super interesting to read.</p>

							</div>

